Face Generation¶

In this project, you'll use generative adversarial networks to generate new images of faces.

Get the Data¶

You'll be using two datasets in this project:

  • MNIST
  • CelebA

Since the celebA dataset is complex and you're doing GANs in a project for the first time, we want you to test your neural network on MNIST before CelebA. Running the GANs on MNIST will allow you to see how well your model trains sooner.

If you're using FloydHub, set data_dir to "/input" and use the FloydHub data ID "R5KrjnANiKVhLWAkpXhNBe".

Preprocess the Data¶

Since the project's main focus is on building the GANs, we'll preprocess the data for you. The values of the MNIST and CelebA dataset will be in the range of -0.5 to 0.5 of 28x28 dimensional images. The CelebA images will be cropped to remove parts of the image that don't include a face, then resized down to 28x28.

The MNIST images are black and white images with a single color channel while the CelebA images have 3 color channels (RGB color channel).

Build the Neural Network¶

You'll build the components necessary to build a GANs by implementing the following functions below:

  • model_inputs
  • discriminator
  • generator
  • model_loss
  • model_opt
  • train

Discriminator¶

Implement discriminator to create a discriminator neural network that discriminates on images. This function should be able to reuse the variables in the neural network. Use tf.variable_scope with a scope name of "discriminator" to allow the variables to be reused. The function should return a tuple of (tensor output of the discriminator, tensor logits of the discriminator).

In [6]:
def discriminator(images, reuse=False):
    """
    Create the discriminator network
    :param images: Tensor of input image(s)
    :param reuse: Boolean if the weights should be reused
    :return: Tuple of (tensor output of the discriminator, tensor logits of the discriminator)
    """
    # Discriminator Design Notes: 
    #
    # For more details on how the discriminator please see the description notes found in the 
    # generator definition in this project. 
    #
    # Discriminator Design Summary: 
    # - Replace any pooling layers with strided convolutions.
    # - Use batch normilization layers. 
    # - Remove fully connected hidden layers.
    # - Use LeakyReLU activation function for all layers. 
    #
    # TODO: Implement Function
    Alpha = 0.2
    Kernal_Size = 4
    
    with tf.variable_scope('discriminator', reuse=reuse):
        # Image input layer is 32x32x3
        Layer_1 = tf.layers.conv2d(images, 64, Kernal_Size, strides=2, padding='same')
        Leaky_Relu_1 = tf.maximum(Alpha * Layer_1, Layer_1)
        # Image reshaped to 16x16x64 tensor. 
        
        Layer_2 = tf.layers.conv2d(Leaky_Relu_1, 128, Kernal_Size, strides=2, padding='same')
        Batch_Norm_2 = tf.layers.batch_normalization(Layer_2, training=True)
        Leaky_Relu_2 = tf.maximum(Alpha * Batch_Norm_2, Batch_Norm_2)
        # Image reshaped to 8x8x128 tensor.
        
        Layer_3 = tf.layers.conv2d(Leaky_Relu_2, 256, Kernal_Size, strides=2, padding='same')
        Batch_Norm_3 = tf.layers.batch_normalization(Layer_3, training=True)
        Leaky_Relu_3 = tf.maximum(Alpha * Batch_Norm_3, Batch_Norm_3)
        # Image reshaped to 4x4x256 tensor. 

        # Flatten it
        # Note: 256 is the maximum size the flatten layer can be. The helper.py has set his image size
        # for the dataset.
        Flatten_Layer = tf.reshape(Leaky_Relu_3, (-1, 4*4*256))
        logits = tf.layers.dense(Flatten_Layer, 1)
        out = tf.sigmoid(logits)
        
        return out, logits

Generator¶

Implement generator to generate an image using z. This function should be able to reuse the variables in the neural network. Use tf.variable_scope with a scope name of "generator" to allow the variables to be reused. The function should return the generated 28 x 28 x out_channel_dim images.

In [7]:
def generator(z, out_channel_dim, is_train=True):
    """
    Create the generator network
    :param z: Input z
    :param out_channel_dim: The number of channels in the output image
    :param is_train: Boolean if generator is being used for training
    :return: The tensor output of the generator
    """
    # Generator Design Notes: 
    # - Reference: "Unsupervised Representation Learning with Deep Convulutional Generative Adversarial Networks"
    #              by Alec Radford, Luke Metz, and Soumith Chintala
    # 
    # Using the literature provided in the reference above the authors discuss that "historical attempts to scale up GANs
    # using CNNs to model images have been unsuccessful." They outline some different methods to develop the architecture
    # of their networks. 
    #
    # First, instead of using maxpooling layers commonaly found in the development of CNN architectures they opted to use 
    # strided convolutions. This replacement allowed their generator to "learn its own spatial upsampling". The 
    # generator designed in this project will follow a similar method. Second, the authors opted to only apply fully 
    # connected layers to input and output of the geneator and output of the discremantor. The goal of this 
    # to find a middle ground between model stability and convergence speed. 
    #
    # Third, several batch normilization layers are used to help with training probelms caused by poor initialization 
    # and supports the gradient flow in deeper models. According to the authors "this proved critical to get deep 
    # generators to begin learning, preventing the generator from collapsing all samples to a single point 
    # which is common failure mdoe observed in GANs". 
    #
    # Lastly, the leaky ReLU activation function is used in the generator with the exception of the output layer which uses
    # the hyperbolic tangent function. Applying a bounded activation function "allowed the model to learn
    # more quickly to saturate and cover the color space of the training distribution". 
    #
    # Generator Design Summary: 
    # - Replace any pooling layers with fractional-strided convolutions.
    # - Use batch normilization. 
    # - Remove fully connected hidden layers.
    # - Use ReLU activation function in generator for all yaers execept for the output, which use Tanh. 
    
    # TODO: Implement Function
    Alpha = 0.2 
    Kernal_Size = 4
        
    with tf.variable_scope('generator', reuse=not is_train):
        # First fully connected layer
        FCL_1 = tf.layers.dense(z, 4*4*512)
        
        # Reshape Fully Connected Layer to start convolutional stack.
        ConvL_1 = tf.reshape(FCL_1, (-1, 4, 4, 512))
        ConvL_1_Batch = tf.layers.batch_normalization(ConvL_1, training = is_train)
        ConvL_1_LReLU = tf.maximum(Alpha*ConvL_1_Batch, ConvL_1_Batch)
        
        ConvL_2 = tf.layers.conv2d_transpose(ConvL_1_LReLU, 256, Kernal_Size, strides = 1, padding = 'valid')
        ConvL_2_Batch = tf.layers.batch_normalization(ConvL_2, training = is_train)
        ConvL_2_LReLU = tf.maximum(Alpha*ConvL_2_Batch, ConvL_2_Batch)
        
        ConvL_3 = tf.layers.conv2d_transpose(ConvL_2_LReLU, 128, Kernal_Size, strides = 2, padding = 'same')
        ConvL_3_Batch = tf.layers.batch_normalization(ConvL_3, training = is_train)
        ConvL_3_LReLU = tf.maximum(Alpha*ConvL_3_Batch, ConvL_3_Batch)
        
        # Output Layer
        Logits = tf.layers.conv2d_transpose(ConvL_3_LReLU, out_channel_dim, Kernal_Size, strides = 2, padding = 'same')
        
        Output = tf.tanh(Logits)         
        
        
    return Output

Loss¶

Implement model_loss to build the GANs for training and calculate the loss. The function should return a tuple of (discriminator loss, generator loss). Use the following functions you implemented:

  • discriminator(images, reuse=False)
  • generator(z, out_channel_dim, is_train=True)
In [8]:
import numpy as np

def model_loss(input_real, input_z, out_channel_dim):
    """
    Get the loss for the discriminator and generator
    :param input_real: Images from the real dataset
    :param input_z: Z input
    :param out_channel_dim: The number of channels in the output image
    :return: A tuple of (discriminator loss, generator loss)
    """
    # TODO: Implement Function
    
    # First, let's create our generator model so that we will have inputs for our "fake" discrimnator.
    Gen_Model = generator(input_z, out_channel_dim, is_train = True)
    
    # Now let us create two discriminator models. The first will be using the "fake" inputs from the 
    # generator model and the second will use the "real" inputs passed into this function. 
    # Remember the goal is to test how good our generator model is at tricking our discriminator model
    # and so that is why we need a "real" and "fake" discriminator models to be created.
    D_Model_Real, D_Logits_Real = discriminator(input_real, reuse = False)
    D_Model_Fake, D_Logits_Fake = discriminator(Gen_Model, reuse = True)
    
    # To determine our loss we need to examine the loss being generated by not only the generator 
    # model, but also both of the discriminator models. A useufal way for determining the loss is
    # by using a cross-entorpy function such as the sigmoid activation function. Afterwards, we 
    # can use another function provided in TensorFlow called "tf.reduce_mean" that will allow 
    # for us to generate a single element output from our tensor. 
    
    # Note: There are two differences between the two discriminator loss calculations below. First,
    # the "fake" version uses zeros for its labels versus the "real" using ones for its labels. 
    # The goal of this is because we want our discriminator to output a 1 if an image is real and
    # a zero if the output is fake. In order to do so we need to set up the losses to reflect that.
    # Second, we are reducing the size of the "real" discriminator's labels by applying a smoother. 
    # The goal of the smoother is to help the discriminator generalize better. This is known as 
    # label smoothing, typically used with classifiers to improve performance. We will use a 
    # uniform distribution for our smoother instead of applying a fixed value so that we can 
    # simulate more noise into our system. 
    Smoother = np.random.uniform(0.8, 1.0)
    
    D_Loss_Real = tf.reduce_mean(tf.nn.sigmoid_cross_entropy_with_logits(logits = D_Logits_Real,
                                                                         labels = tf.ones_like(D_Logits_Real) * Smoother))
    
    D_Loss_Fake = tf.reduce_mean(tf.nn.sigmoid_cross_entropy_with_logits(logits = D_Logits_Fake, 
                                                                        labels = tf.zeros_like(D_Logits_Real)))
    
    
    G_Loss = tf.reduce_mean(tf.nn.sigmoid_cross_entropy_with_logits(logits = D_Logits_Fake, 
                                                                        labels = tf.ones_like(D_Logits_Real)))
    
    
    # Finally, we will calculate all of the loss found by our discriminators and output the 
    # total discriminator loss as well as the generator loss.
    D_Loss = D_Loss_Real + D_Loss_Fake
      
    
    return D_Loss, G_Loss

Optimization¶

Implement model_opt to create the optimization operations for the GANs. Use tf.trainable_variables to get all the trainable variables. Filter the variables with names that are in the discriminator and generator scope names. The function should return a tuple of (discriminator training operation, generator training operation).

In [9]:
def model_opt(d_loss, g_loss, learning_rate, beta1):
    """
    Get optimization operations
    :param d_loss: Discriminator loss Tensor
    :param g_loss: Generator loss Tensor
    :param learning_rate: Learning Rate Placeholder
    :param beta1: The exponential decay rate for the 1st moment in the optimizer
    :return: A tuple of (discriminator training operation, generator training operation)
    """
    # TODO: Implement Function
    # Because we want to update the generator and discriminator variables separately we 
    # need to get the variables for each part and build optimizers for each. 
    Train_Vars = tf.trainable_variables()
    Gen_Vars = [var for var in Train_Vars if var.name.startswith('generator')]
    Dis_Vars = [var for var in Train_Vars if var.name.startswith('discriminator')]
    
    with tf.control_dependencies(tf.get_collection(tf.GraphKeys.UPDATE_OPS)):
        Dis_Train_Opt = tf.train.AdamOptimizer(learning_rate, beta1 = beta1).minimize(d_loss, var_list = Dis_Vars)
        Gen_Train_Opt = tf.train.AdamOptimizer(learning_rate, beta1 = beta1).minimize(g_loss, var_list = Gen_Vars)
    
    return Dis_Train_Opt, Gen_Train_Opt

Show Output¶

Use this function to show the current output of the generator during training. It will help you determine how well the GANs is training.

"""
DON'T MODIFY ANYTHING IN THIS CELL
"""
import numpy as np

def show_generator_output(sess, n_images, input_z, out_channel_dim, image_mode):
    """
    Show example output for the generator
    :param sess: TensorFlow session
    :param n_images: Number of Images to display
    :param input_z: Input Z Tensor
    :param out_channel_dim: The number of channels in the output image
    :param image_mode: The mode to use for images ("RGB" or "L")
    """
    cmap = None if image_mode == 'RGB' else 'gray'
    z_dim = input_z.get_shape().as_list()[-1]
    example_z = np.random.uniform(-1, 1, size=[n_images, z_dim])

    samples = sess.run(
        generator(input_z, out_channel_dim, False),
        feed_dict={input_z: example_z})

    images_grid = helper.images_square_grid(samples, image_mode)
    pyplot.imshow(images_grid, cmap=cmap)
    pyplot.show()

Train¶

Implement train to build and train the GANs. Use the following functions you implemented:

  • model_inputs(image_width, image_height, image_channels, z_dim)
  • model_loss(input_real, input_z, out_channel_dim)
  • model_opt(d_loss, g_loss, learning_rate, beta1)

Use the show_generator_output to show generator output while you train. Running show_generator_output for every batch will drastically increase training time and increase the size of the notebook. It's recommended to print the generator output every 100 batches.

import time

def train(epoch_count, batch_size, z_dim, learning_rate, beta1, get_batches, data_shape, data_image_mode):
    """
    Train the GAN
    :param epoch_count: Number of epochs
    :param batch_size: Batch Size
    :param z_dim: Z dimension
    :param learning_rate: Learning Rate
    :param beta1: The exponential decay rate for the 1st moment in the optimizer
    :param get_batches: Function to get batches
    :param data_shape: Shape of the data
    :param data_image_mode: The image mode to use for images ("RGB" or "L")
    """
    # TODO: Build Model
    # To build the model we must first know what our model inputs are. Luckily, we 
    # created a function for this earlier called "model_inputs". Now, all we have to 
    # do is provide that function with the shape of our input data. 
    Image_Width, Image_Height, Image_Channels = data_shape[1], data_shape[2], data_shape[3]
    
    inputs_real, inputs_z, learn_rate = model_inputs(Image_Width, Image_Height, Image_Channels, z_dim)
    
    # Now that we have our inputs we can build our loss and optimizer models.
    D_Loss, G_Loss = model_loss(inputs_real, inputs_z, Image_Channels)
    D_Opt, G_Opt = model_opt(D_Loss, G_Loss, learn_rate, beta1)
    
    # Also, we will throw in a saver function to save our model for future use.
    Saver = tf.train.Saver()
    
    steps = 0
    with tf.Session() as sess:
        Training_Session_Time = time.time()
        sess.run(tf.global_variables_initializer())
        for epoch_i in range(epoch_count):
            Start_Time = time.time()
            for batch_images in get_batches(batch_size):
                # TODO: Train Model
                
                # ***** Start Time does not affect training *****
                # I am implementing the start time function here in order to gain 
                # some insight on the run time comparisons as I adjust the model. 
                steps += 1
                
                batch_images = batch_images * 2
                batch_z = np.random.uniform(-1, 1, size=(batch_size, z_dim))

                _ = sess.run(D_Opt, feed_dict={inputs_real: batch_images, inputs_z: batch_z, learn_rate: learning_rate})
                _ = sess.run(G_Opt, feed_dict={inputs_z: batch_z, inputs_real: batch_images, learn_rate: learning_rate})
                
                
                if steps % 100 == 0:
                    train_loss_d = D_Loss.eval({inputs_z: batch_z, inputs_real: batch_images})
                    train_loss_g = G_Loss.eval({inputs_z: batch_z, inputs_real: batch_images})
                    
                    print("Epoch {}/{} Step {}...".format(epoch_i+1, epoch_count, steps),
                          "Discriminator Loss: {:.4f}...".format(train_loss_d),
                          "Generator Loss: {:.4f}".format(train_loss_g),
                          "... Elapsed Time ={:.4f}".format(time.time() - Start_Time)) 
                    
                if steps % 100 == 0:
                    show_generator_output(sess, 16, inputs_z, Image_Channels, data_image_mode)
                    
        print("Total Training Session Time: {:.4f}".format(time.time() - Training_Session_Time))
                
        Saver.save(sess, './Generator_Model_Train.ckpt')

MNIST¶

Test your GANs architecture on MNIST. After 2 epochs, the GANs should be able to generate images that look like handwritten digits. Make sure the loss of the generator is lower than the loss of the discriminator or close to 0.

Submitting This Project¶

When submitting this project, make sure to run all the cells before saving the notebook. Save the notebook file as "dlnd_face_generation.ipynb" and save it as a HTML file under "File" -> "Download as". Include the "helper.py" and "problem_unittests.py" files in your submission.
